prompt: Find enzymes with endogenous substrates that have no pharmacology to speak of?
completion: SELECT e.* FROM enzyme e WHERE e.enzyme_id NOT IN (SELECT p.enzyme_id FROM pharmacology p);

prompt: List all ligands relevant for immunopharmacology.
completion: SELECT l.* FROM ligand l WHERE l.in_gtip = TRUE;

prompt: Get ligands that are antimalarial.
completion: SELECT l.* FROM ligand l WHERE l.in_gtmp = TRUE;

prompt: Retrieve clinical trials linked to a specific ligand.
completion: SELECT ct.* FROM clinical_trial ct JOIN ligand2clinical_trials lct ON ct.clinical_trial_id = lct.clinical_trial_id WHERE lct.ligand_id = ?;

prompt: Find peptides linked to a ligand and their precursors.
completion: SELECT p.*, prec.* FROM peptide p JOIN precursor2peptide pp ON p.peptide_id = pp.peptide_id JOIN precursor prec ON pp.precursor_id = prec.precursor_id WHERE pp.ligand_id = ?;

prompt: Get the reference details for interactions.
completion: SELECT r.* FROM reference r JOIN interaction_affinity_refs iar ON r.reference_id = iar.reference_id WHERE iar.interaction_id = ?;

prompt: List the structure and physico-chemical properties for a ligand.
completion: SELECT ls.*, lp.* FROM ligand_structure ls JOIN ligand_physchem lp ON ls.ligand_id = lp.ligand_id WHERE ls.ligand_id = ?;

prompt: Retrieve information about ligand families linked to a specific ligand.
completion: SELECT f.* FROM family f JOIN ligand2family lf ON f.family_id = lf.family_id WHERE lf.ligand_id = ?;

prompt: Find objects related to a specific receptor family.
completion: SELECT o.* FROM object o JOIN receptor2family rf ON o.object_id = rf.object_id WHERE rf.family_id = ?;

prompt: Get all families and their hierarchies.
completion: WITH RECURSIVE family_hierarchy AS ( SELECT g.group_id, f.family_id, f.family_name FROM grouping g JOIN family f ON g.family_id = f.family_id UNION ALL SELECT g.group_id, f.family_id, f.family_name FROM family_hierarchy fh JOIN grouping g ON fh.family_id = g.family_id JOIN family f ON g.group_id = f.family_id ) SELECT * FROM family_hierarchy;
